[[File:121202 - Marayke Jonkers with world champs silver medal - 3b - digital image.jpg|thumb|[[ Marayke Jonkers]] is an SM4 classified swimmer]]
'''S4''', '''SB3''', '''SM4''' are [[Paralympic sports#Classification|disability swimming classifications]] used for categorising swimmers based on their level of disability.

==History==
The classification was created by the [[International Paralympic Committee]]  and has roots in a 2003 attempt to address "the overall objective to support and co-ordinate the ongoing development of accurate, reliable, consistent and credible sport focused classification systems and their implementation."<ref name=ipc-2003>{{cite web|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|title=Paralympic Classification Today|page=3|acccessdate=18 November 2011|date=22 April 2010}}</ref>

==Sport==
This classification is for [[swimming (sport)|swimming]].<ref name=understanding>{{cite web|title=Understanding Classification: A Guide to the Classification Systems used in Paralympic Sports|first=Jane|last=Buckley|date=2011|accessdate=12 November 2011|url=http://www.sportingwheelies.org.au/doc.php?ID=38}}</ref> In the classification title, S represents Freestyle, Backstroke and Butterfly strokes. SB means breaststroke. SM means individual medley.<ref name=understanding/> Jane Buckley, writing for the [[Sporting Wheelies]], describes the swimmers in this classification as having the use of "their arms and have minimal weakness in their hands but have no use of their trunk or legs; Swimmers with coordination problems affecting all limbs but predominantly in the legs; Swimmers with limb loss to 3 limbs. Increasing ability compared to Class S3."<ref name=understanding>{{cite web|title=Understanding Classification: A Guide to the Classification Systems used in Paralympic Sports|first=Jane|last=Buckley|date=2011|accessdate=12 November 2011|url=http://www.sportingwheelies.org.au/doc.php?ID=38}}</ref>

==Competitions==
At the [[2008 Summer Paralympics]], this classification had competitions in the 50m and 100m Freestyle, 200m Freestyle , 50m Backstroke , 50m Butterfly, 50m Breaststroke , and 150m Individual Medley events.<ref name=2008-bejining>{{cite web|url=http://en.paralympic.beijing2008.cn/news/sports/swimming/n214355368.shtml|accessdate=18 November 2011|publisher=The Beijing Organizing Committee for the Games of the XXIX Olympiad|date=2008|title=Swimming Classification}}</ref>

==Competitors==
Swimmers who have competed in this classification include:
* [[Cheryl Angelelli]]<ref name=IPC-class>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/Sport/Results/search.html?sport=20&gender=all&medal=medals&npc=all&games=2008PG|accessdate=18 November 2011|title=Results|publisher=International Paralympic Committee}}</ref>
* [[Aimee Bruder]]<ref name=IPC-class>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/Sport/Results/search.html?sport=20&gender=all&medal=medals&npc=all&games=2008PG|accessdate=18 November 2011|title=Results|publisher=International Paralympic Committee}}</ref>
* [[Nely Miranda]]<ref name=IPC-class>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/Sport/Results/search.html?sport=20&gender=all&medal=medals&npc=all&games=2008PG|accessdate=18 November 2011|title=Results|publisher=International Paralympic Committee}}</ref>

